The better world is already here
KOPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have been discussing the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world where more people mean less food, where rising resource demand leads to plundering and war, and where increasing production capacity over the last decades brings about more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, Limits to Growth, continues to influence the environmental movement to this day.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, living standards, environmental quality, and so on.
They are seen by their opponents as "economists of plenty," who trust the market, which allegedly solves all problems.
But instead of picking facts and stories that fit into a grand narrative of decline or progress, we should try to compare all areas of human existence to see if the world is really getting better or worse.
This is exactly what I aimed to achieve together with 21 globally leading economists by developing a value list covering the last 150 years.
In ten areas – including health, education, war, gender ratios, air pollution, climate change, and biodiversity – the economists answered the same question for each year from 1900 to 2013, including projections up to 2050: How high were the relative costs of this problem in each year?
Based on classical economic evaluations of all factors from deaths, health damages, and illiteracy to the destruction of wetlands to higher hurricane risk due to global warming, the economists show the costs of each individual problem.
To assess the magnitude of the problem, it is compared with the total resources available for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem evident as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 have been partly surprising.
Let's consider gender inequality.
Basically, we excluded almost half of the world population from production back then.
In 1900, only 15% of the workforce worldwide was female.
What are the losses that arose from this small proportion?
Even if we take into account the higher costs of educating women and that someone has to do unpaid household work, the losses amounted to at least 17% of global GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor force participation rate and smaller income differences, the loss is 7% – and it is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It will probably come as a surprise that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to deliver mostly increasing net benefits – rising to annually 1.5% of GDP.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it is only moderate, the benefits outweigh the costs.
On one hand, the higher CO2 yields are a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect at 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, a moderate warming reduces cold-related deaths more than it increases heat-related deaths.
It also reduces heating needs more than it creates new cooling needs, amounting to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, which cost around 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems like wetlands, resulting in a loss of about 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, costs increase and benefits decrease, dramatically reducing the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs for the world, which justifies cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the valuation list also shows that the world's biggest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, putting things into perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful gases from cooking and heating, representing a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in 1900, these costs equated to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved most significantly worldwide.
Until the late 18th century, human life expectancy hardly changed.
The gain since 1900 cannot be overstated: At that time, global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is at 69 years (and likely to be 76 years by 2050).
The largest influencing factor was the decline in childhood mortality.
For example, only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio in 1970.
In 2000, it was 85%, which led to saving three million lives every year – more than would have been saved by world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than 2.5 billion USD on vaccines and promised an additional 10 billion.
Through efforts by the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, polio cases have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the costs of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century amounted to astounding 32% of global GDP.
Today, they have dropped to about 11% and will halve again by 2050.
Even though optimists are not entirely correct in all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century likely costs around 1% of GDP annually, and more in some places), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the topics examined show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the general trend is even clearer.
Relative to the resources available to combat these issues, global problems have dramatically decreased.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no problems anymore.
Even though they have become smaller in areas like health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still significant.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has improved greatly.
In addition, the scoring list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not orient our view of the future towards the most terrifying stories or the loudest interest groups, but towards objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
